m)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=982.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Dying Earth problem solutions</span><hr size=1> There are several plausible and achievable /by the nowadays envisioned and prognosed technology/ solutions, not only to contineau the existence of earth`s life in general, but to keep on the life as we know it, and to persist to be humans in comperativelly normal earth environment /if our progeny find it necesarry and valuable to stick on our full of limitatioins species characteristics/. <br>
Inevitably after about 5-7 bln years the Sun will become 100 times bigger in diameter and 1000 times in luminosity. Long before /about 1 bln years after present/ it will become too hot for life as we know it to be sustained on Earth. <br>
NO matter whether we colonize the Universe, beyond the sollar system, or the bodies within it, or artificial worlds... /the proposed habitat types are uncountable/, we have to have in mind that our descendants /at least part of them/ could wish to preserve their biological old-fashioned humanity and hence, the Earth in very-near to present state, motivated by santimental reasons or else, non-economical motives.<br>
<br>
Part of the solutions of the problem of the heating sun are:<br>
1. Most simple - shadow the Earth with parasol, and magnetically deflect the increased plasma density of the interplanetary space in it`s vicinity after Sun becomes a red giant. Make the parasol activelly transforming the red light of the old sun in the present-day light spectrum. After the sun becomes white dwarf - collect the scarse light and point in toward the earth in a single colimated spot by pseudo-white laser beam. It could be easily calculated for how long /dozens of billions of years/ the 'geothermal' source from the dying sun will be enough, before it becomes black dwarf. For such long period the Earth non-solid spheres could be replenished entirelly from inside if necesarry.<br>
2. Move the Earth toward the outer system, gradually by means of gravity assist with big asteroids, paralelly and in dependence of the increasement of the sun emision`s intensity. Even in the Kuipert belt after 5-7 billions of years it shall be in the a.k.a. 'Delayed Gratification Habitanble Zone' lasting at least several tens or hundreds of millions years. After the sun final transformation in white dwarf - collect and redirect it`s light, toward thec earth`s biosphere.<br>
3. Control the sun through David Criswell`s 'stellar husbandry' = 'star lifting'. He thinks that if we manage to control the fusion in sun`s core in more efficient and slow manner, we could contineau, the normal and undisturbed work of the reactor with four powers in magnitude, i.e. calm/good sun for not just 5-7 bln years more but for 50-70 or even hundred TRILLIONS...<br>
<br>
There isn`t unsolvable problem with enough funding. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 470<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/25/03 8:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=982.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Dying Earth problem solutions</span><hr size=1> Thank you Karov for mentioning Stellar Husbandry and such interventions we could make to begin changing the nature and appearence of the sky.<br>
<br>
In his list of potential and impending calamities facing us, Tim didn't mention that in about 5Bn years, the M-31 galaxy in Andromeda will start colliding with ours...<br>
<br>
Beyond Criswell's plan to extend the life of the Sun for a few hundred billion years, we'll have to spread across the galaxy and beyond into the intergalactic void (which is probably still full of dark matter comets).<br>
 M-31 leaves us no choice but to spread far off this one mudball.<br>
<br>
An option is to leave the solar system -Sun, Earth, Dyson cloud of space habitats and all. Use the Stellar controls to eject plasma out of one polar region,and extend magnetic fields far out ahead of the Sun, to make it a Bussard ramscoop engine, with the Sun as the motor, and the solar gravity carrying the planets we take along with our Dyson cloud civilization.<br>
By that time, we'll have to have figured our how to control and modulate the geomagnetic field as well as the Sun's fields.<br>
<br>
All the inhabited systems who want to go on living after the collision will have to become intergalactic nomads, at least to the point of orbiting the twin colliding galaxies out beyond the range of the worst effects.<br>
 The clusters orbiting the galaxy will become colonized -probably before this point- but they won't be alone as all the inhabited systems move out too.  (8-12 billion years from now, when the galactic collision will be well underway, with the 2 spirals being mixed together and warped beyond recognition due to gravity of the 2 masses)<br>
<br>
 I'm not sure if anybody (except maybe Freeman Dyson) has thought about evolving our capabilities to controlling the movement of galaxies. <br>
Really, the heavens are wild, wasteful chaos (as are planets if we don't intervene and control weather and tectonics and such).<br>
 Lots of stars extravagently blowing their lives away because they're too big. Stars wandering uncontrolled past others,  disturbing the planetry orbits. Lots of wild uncontrolled or un-harvested interstellar comets that wander through, causing a mass extinction every few hundred million years... Galaxies smashing through each other, tossing solar systems worth of useful mass out into intergalactic space, beyond reach for use.<br>
<br>
 Very untidy. We really should get our acts together and do something about all this. As the only known sentient tool-using planners in all the galaxies, it's up to us. (any others out there are on their own, unless they speak up and join in).<br>
 The geological-era lifespan of Gaian life is largely beyond we puny ephemeral individuals, but the responsibility to preserve biodiversity is ours -each and every one of us as members of this funny confused species.<br>
In all this universe the most precious thing is biodiversity, maybe second only to hope and sentience -as in imagination &amp; creativity and planning ways to make things better. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A> at: 12/25/03 8:38 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/Bio-02.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 292<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/26/03 4:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=982.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Spot on!</span><hr size=1> We need to get off of our collective arse’s and do something.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
